Historically, divorce carried a significant social stigma, as it was often seen as a failure to uphold one's familial responsibilities or an inability to maintain harmony. While contemporary Chinese society has become much more open, and divorce is legally accessible and increasingly common in urban areas, there remains a pervasive cultural sentiment that a marriage should be maintained through compromise and patience whenever possible. Many still view the dissolution of a family as a grave and unfortunate matter. Consequently, while it is widely understood that divorce is necessary in cases of abuse or irreconcilable breakdown, it is rarely viewed as something to be encouraged or taken lightly. The prevailing view balances the modern recognition of personal autonomy with a conservative emphasis on the sanctity of the family bond.

